│ is the verifier failure. There is no intermediate debug-only output from      │
│ ipsccp, which means the transformation happened silently through              │
│ SCCPSolver::tryToReplaceWithConstant. That routine performs a                 │
│ Value::replaceAllUsesWith(Const) when it decides a lattice value is constant  │
│ (or undef). The lifetime.start argument was rewritten, triggering the         │
│ verifier error. No other transformations are implicated earlier.\n\n3. Root   │
│ Cause Analysis:\nAllocaInst values represent unique stack objects. IPSCCP's   │
│ lattice for an alloca starts as \"not null\" (visitAllocaInst marks it with   │
│ markNotNull). Predicate refinement (equality test against a constant pointer) │
│ can incorrectly conclude the original alloca value itself is equal to that    │
│ constant across its uses in a dominated block, and then marks it as a         │
│ constant. SCCP's semantics allow path-sensitive constants to be propagated    │
│ only when a value is constant on all executable paths; here, it confused a    │
│ path-local equality (inside the taken branch of the comparison) with a global │
│ constant fact for the defining value. Once the lattice entry was marked       │
│ constant inttoptr(-1), tryToReplaceWithConstant replaced all uses—including   │
│ the operand to llvm.lifetime.start—producing invalid IR (because              │
│ lifetime.start requires the original alloca or poison). A fully correct fix   │
│ would prevent the lattice for an AllocaInst from becoming an arbitrary        │
│ pointer constant derived from conditional                                     │
