  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nRunning ipsccp on the reproducer
causes the pass to replace the alloca value %a with the constant inttoptr(-1)
globally. This turns the comparison into a constant true, keeps the (formerly
dead) if block, and leaves a llvm.lifetime.start intrinsic whose operand is now
inttoptr(-1). The verifier rightfully rejects this: lifetime.start/end require an
alloca or poison operand. The crash therefore stems from IPSCCP performing an
invalid replacement of an AllocaInst with a non-alloca constant pointer.\n\n2.
Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe only emitted message is the verifier failure; no
intermediate debug output appears because the offending transformation is a
silent use-replacement done by SCCPSolver::tryToReplaceWithConstant. That routine
looks for a lattice state proven constant (or narrowed to a single element range)
and then performs V->replaceAllUsesWith(Const). There is no safeguard against
replacing allocas. The resulting IR violates intrinsic constraints before dead
code cleanup removes the now-reachable block.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nPredicateInfo plus handlePredicate can (under an equality branch)
merge a constant pointer lattice value into the defining value (the alloca),
incorrectly upgrading path-local equality information to a global constant fact.
Once the lattice for the alloca becomes that constant, tryToReplaceWithConstant
replaces all its uses, including the operand to llvm.lifetime.start. Because
allocas represent distinct stack storage whose address is not a fixed integral
constant, treating them as arbitrary constant pointers is unsound. Even if the
branch later proves unreachable, the replacement already polluted IR. The minimal
and reliable fix is to prevent tryToReplaceWithConstant from substituting
AllocaInst results with constants (other than poison, which verifier allows).
This preserves intrinsic operand invariants and avoids introducing incorrect
control-flow folding based on the fabricated constant address.\n\n4. Proposed
Edit Point(s):\nFile: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SCCPSolver.cpp lines 61-88
(inside SCCPSolver::tryToReplaceWithConstant).\nChange: After computing Const and
before performing the replacement, add a guard:\n- If V is an AllocaInst, do not
replace it with a constant pointer (return false). Optionally allow replacement
only if the constant is PoisonValue (which is already produced elsewhere when
appropriate). Add a comment explaining the interaction with lifetime.start/end
intrinsics and path-local predicate refinements.\nRationale: This localized
change prevents generation of invalid IR while leaving existing constant
propagation for other pointer-producing instructions intact. It addresses the
verifier failure without altering broader solver behavior.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy
adding a conservative check in tryToReplaceWithConstant to skip replacing allocas
by arbitrary constants, we stop IPSCCP from producing invalid IR for lifetime
intrinsics and from globally applying branch-local equalities to allocas. The
verifier no longer aborts on the reproducer, and the pass remains correct for
other cases. Further refinement (e.g., constraining handlePredicate for pointer
equality) can be considered later, but this minimal fix resolves the immediate
crash safely.\n",
